I think you are getting confused with javascript&#39;s synchronous &amp; its &#39;asynchronous&#39; behavior. ```app.post``` takes a &#39;callback&#39;. A &#39;callback&#39; is a function that will be called in some abritaty amount of time &amp; in your case... when you receive an HTTP request. When your code is executed, your ```axios.post``` function will execute before the callback passed to ```app.post```. So all the keys in ```data``` will be never be defined... Not to mention variables; ```name, age, phone``` are never declared in the scope they are being used. 

I would suggest creating a generic function that takes arguments ```name, age, phone``` and executes the ```axios.post``` logic. Therefore you can reuse this function on each ```app.post```. I&#39;ve created a code snippet below of what you could do. Its using [Promises](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Promise) and [async/await](https://javascript.info/async-await) to manage asynchronous activity. 


```
